reviewText: Like the other Attitude Collection DVD I have, Unforgiven 98, this one's DVD production quality is "unforgiveable" *gets pelted with rotten fruit* for its abysmal production.  Released in 2002, well into the WWF's DVD history releases, this one has NO chapters, NO menus, NO extras, NOTHING.  To get from one match to the next, you have to manually fast forward like a VHS.  At least in Unforgiven 98, they had a mid-way point in the event, essentially creating two 90 minute chapters in the 3 hour event.  This one had nothing.The event itself was a lackluster one, especially by the WWF's "Attitude Era" standards.  By modern WWE standards, it would've been a spellbinding spectacle.Val Venis and The Godfather vs D'Lo Brown and Mark HenryThis was a surprise, considering how little I think of all these superstars, and their initial fates in the WWF as low-card players most of their careers.  They did some good stuff, but nothing that was especially spectacular.  (6.5/10)The Headbangers vs The OdditiesI was a wrestling fan since around early 2000 and as a child back then, I used to scour the depths of WWF.com's old video archive.  Along the way, I encountered these guys... The Oddities.  I knew of the Headbangers from my Wrestlemania 2000 game, as well as on TV, and so I knew what to expect.  What I did not expect was the odd show the Oddities put on, with the 7 foot Kurrgan, looking like a thick Russian guy trying to fit in with a strange group, the other 7+ foot Silva looking like a thick Italian guy trying to fit in with a strange group, and I was amused.  While not a great wrestler, Kurrgan had amazing ring presence and charisma, and Golga was surprising despite his size.  This match wasn't about wrestling, but rather entertainment.  (8/10)Steve Blackman vs Owen HartThis one was a boring match of locks, holds, fluffy light wrestling moves, and Owen Hart threatening to get counted out many times until he finally does get counted out.  Garbage at worst, below average at best.  (3/10)The Brood vs The J.O.B. SquadLike the Oddities vs Headbangers match, I knew of these groups from scouring the old archives of WWF.com and from my Wrestlemania 2000 video game.  I was surprised to see them in action (and to see 2 Cold Scorpio in the WWF) and they put on a great tag team match.  (7.5/10)Striptease MatchJeff Jarrett vs GoldustDull as dishwater is not an overstatement.  For some reason Goldust hasn't impressed me with any of his matches, and there was little that was good about this match.  Even the post-match striptease was something that would make little 12 year olds giggle and press against their doors so their parents wouldn't walk in.  (1/10)WWF Tag Team ChampionshipThe New Age Outlaws (C) vs The Big Boss Man and Ken ShamrockFor some reason, this one was terrible.  The Big Boss Man's performance was something mirroring the ghastly affair of the "Kennel from Hell" match with Al Snow, and more attention seemed to be focused on commissioner Shawn Michaels, being a former DX member, siding against the two DX members, the Road Dogg and Billy Gunn.  (3/10)WWF ChampionshipMankind vs The Rock (C)Mick Foley isn't a great wrestler and neither is The Rock, but both have immense ring presence and charisma that more than makes up for it---it makes them superstars.  This match was not a show of this superstardom.  Perhaps because it was a lowly "In Your House" PPV, this match was sluggish and low, and the ending was just even more terrible, with Mankind winning but McMahon claiming that he knocked out The Rock, and thus The Rock still would hold the title.  (3/10)Buried Alive MatchThe Undertaker vs Stone Cold Steve AustinThis match went on too long, and had too little to offer in the way of entertainment or action.  Three times the two battled back and forth from the grave site to the ring, most of the time crawling around as if they were battering one another to bloody pulps.  Austin was filthy from rolling around half-naked in the dirt, and did little more than punches and kicks.  Boring, badly played out match that didn't impress nor did it entertain.  (0/10)If it weren't for the shoddy DVD production, this would probably be a 3 star event, though not a very good one at that.
summary: 3 stars for the event, 1 star for DVD production quality

reviewText: WWF Rock Bottom:  In Your House was the December '98 PPV show.  It wound up being a good way to finish off the WWF's 1998 PPV schedule.  The Buried Alive match between the Undertaker and Stone Cold Steve Austin was not bad  if you like watching two pro wrestlers who don't have ten moves between  them.  If you are a true WRESTLING fan you will enjoy the WWF Title Match  between Champion- The Rock and Challenger- Mankind.  This match picks right  up where Survivor Series '98 left off.  Another great match was the 6-man  tag between the JOB Squad (Al Snow, Scorpio, and Bob Holly) and the Brood  (Gangrel, Edge, and Christian).  Other matches include:  The Striptease  Match between Jeff Jarrett w/ Debra McMichael and Goldust...with an  appearance by WWF Commissioner Shawn Michaels.  D-Lo Brown and Mark Henry  vs. The Godfather and Val Venis.  The New Age Outlaws battle Ken Shamrock  and the Big Bossman with the WWF Tag Team Titles on the line.  Plus much  more...
Title: WWF: In Your House 26 - Rock Bottom VHS

reviewText: Vinnie Mc's new Corporate Champion, The Rock, puts his WWF title on the line against Mankind in a brutal contest that would serve as a warm-up to  the following three shocking matches they have at the Royal Rumble, St  Valintes Day Masacre and on RAW. Austin and The Undertaker face off in a  great Buried Alive match. The rest of the card is irrelevent but still  highly watchable. A great pay-per-view that brings 1998, the year that saw  the WWF return to the top and the era of Attitude was in it's infancy.
Title: WWF: In Your House 26 - Rock Bottom VHS

reviewText: Hello & welcome to this, this is another review in my retro Wrestling Pay Per View reviews that I have been doing for over 2 years. Now earlier this week I reviewed the very bad Capital Carnage but now I am going to review the very last WWF Pay Per View from 1998 Rock Bottom. The year before last Pay Per View of 97 ended with a very sour note after an intense year The WWF had an even better 1998 & they were looking forward to 1999 the companies biggest if not the biggest money making year in WWR WWE history. But did the final Pay Per View of the year end on whimper or a bang after an awesome year I'd want something decent. These reviews especially The WWF stuff mainly for people who grew up watching The Attitude Era mainly that's who it's intended for but you could've missed out on it & are interested in The Attitude Era or you just randomly found this review which is how I believe my reviews are read just randomly someone came across it. Now what has happened since Survivor Series on The November 16th episode of RAW IS WAR Stone Cold Steve Austin got a shot at The WWF Championship against The Rock during this match The Undertaker came out & hit Austin with a Shovel causing a DQ. On the following Sunday Night Heat Vince McMahon knew Austin would enter The Royal Rumble in January Vince said Austin has to qualify he put put him in a Buried Alive Match against The Undertake. It was also announced that Austin had blacked out after a match earlier in the day in San Jose. The next night on RAW IS WAR The Undertaker & Paul Bearer was at the hospital Paul Bearer put Austin out with some Ether they put him in a Hearse they took him out to some wooded area they were going to bury Austin alive but Undertaker came up with the idea to Embalm Austin alive. So they go some kind of Morgue or Funeral Home to do this Kane comes out of nowhere & goes after The Undertaker Austin comes to & escaped which leads to the next week on RAW IS WAR. Austin had a Shovel & was looking for The Undertaker. The Undertaker locked Austin in a Freezer he went to the ring & called Kane out Paul Bearer came out with some Orderlies they were going to have Kane sent to an Asylum. They showed where The Freezer Door was open Kane freed Austin The Undertaker found Kane & knocked him out he had Paul go get The Orderlies he was going to put Kane in what looked like a Body Bag. Austin showed up knocked The Undertaker out with a Shovel he put Undertaker in The Body Bag so The Undertaker was sent to The Asylum. Later on Stone Cold & Kane got Paul Bearer they took him to the ring & Austin messed with Paul bad like he had Kane get a can of gas then he took a pair of scissor's & threatened to stab him in the chest. They took Paul Bearer outside & threw him in The Sewer. The next week on RAW IS WAR while Austin was cutting a promo The Undertaker came over The PA System & an Undertaker Cross lowered he said he will sacrifice Austin tonight. Later on that night Austin teamed with Mankind & The Undertaker teamed up with The Rock the match ended in a disqualification when The Corporation interfered & attacked Mankind The Undertaker had Austin knocked out he had Druids place Austin on The Cross to close the show. On The November 22nd episode of Sunday Night Heat Vince McMahon announced The Rock would defend The WWF Championship against Mankind. On The November 30th episode of RAW IS WAR The Rock helped The Big Boss Man defeat Mankind in a Ladder Match to win The WWF Hardcore Championship. On The November 23rd episode of RAW IS WAR Shawn Michaels was named the new WWF Commissioner he gave X Pac a shot at The WWF Championship during the match later on that night Shawn took a chair & hit X Pac with it & joined The Corporation. The following week on RAW IS WAR called Shawn Michaels made him defend The European title against Ken Shamrock & Shamrock's Intercontinental title would not be on the line. During the match Michaels interfered & along with The Big Boss Man they beat up X Pac then a returning Triple H made the save. Now The Corporation was making offers to The New Age Outlaws. On The December 7th episode  of RAW IS WAR Triple H called out The New Age Outlaws & they revealed they were corporate & Triple H & Shawn Michaels had an entertaining back & forth. Michaels put Triple H & X Pac in a match against Ken Shamrock & The Big Boss Man with a no disqualification stipulation. Later on that night Billy Gunn hit Ken Shamrock with a chair & stuck with  DX. Back on The September 28th episode of RAW IS WAR Owen Hart injured the neck of Dan "Beast" Severn he felt guilty for it so he retired. Then you had The Blue Blazer show up everyone knew it was Owen Hart is Dan "The Beast" Severn over it but he started attacking Severn. Steve Blackman then targeted Owen Hart he thought he was The Blue Blazer but The Blazer showed up with Owen Hart. Blackman kept up with it on The December 6th episode of Heat Owen announced he was returning to the right over Steve Blackman. Goldust thought that Debra was propositioning him on The December 6th episode of Heat he challenged Jeff Jarrett to a Striptease Match where if he won Debra would have to strip if he lost he would have to strip.  On The November 23rd episode of RAW IS WAR Duane Gill defeated Christian to win The WWF Lightheavyweight Championship. That is the backstory leading into this event. The buyrate was a 0.78 that is up from D Generation X In Your House that got a 0.44.The champions at the time wereWWF Champion The Rock November 15th 1998WWF Intercontinental Champions Ken Shamrock October 12th 1998WWF European Champion X Pac October 18th 1998WWF Tag Team Champions The New Age Outlaws Road Dogg Jesse James & BA Billy Gunn August 30th 1998WWF Women's Champion Sable November 15th 1998WWF Lightheavyweight Championship Duane Gill November 17th 1998 match aired November 23rd 1998WWF Hardcore Champion The Big Boss Man November 30th 1998Date December 13, 1998Attendance 20,042Venue General Motors PlaceCity Vancouver, British ColumbiaHeatVince McMahon came out he was soundly booed by The Canadian Fans he told the fans there's no chance inh  e  ll that Stone Cold will ever again be The World Wrestling Federation Champion. All of his hopes will be buried alive. He said that this Pay Per View is dedicated to The Rock the best d  **  n WWF Champion ever. He had 2 giant promotional photos of The Rock revealed. Then he went after The Canadian Fans. Then he had Shane come out he did some commentary for Heat.WWF Lightheavyweight ChampionshipChampion Duane Gill with The JOB Squad Def Matt Hardy with Jeff Hardy DUDThe Blue Meanie interfered.They showed where earlier in the day where Michael Cole was interviewing The Rock & was attacked by Mankind & this was f  *  *  * in  g hilarious.In the back they show The Trainer tell The Rock that he can't go The Rock tells McMahon to tell Mankind hes  crew  e  d himself out of a title shot.Mankind came out he announced that in the contract they signed that it states if The Rock for whatever reason can't compete he has to forfit Mankind's remixed music was awesome.Kevin Quinn Def Brian Christopher with Scott Taylor DUDTriple H with DX Def Droz with Animal DUDShawn Michaels came out to tell The New Age Outlaws they compete on Heat as a warm up match.When they come back from the break they ask Vince McMahon from the back if The Rock was going to give up the title McMahon said The Rock isn't giving up the title & he will reach some sort of agreement with Mankind.Jeff Jarrett & Debra came out & they were interviewed by Michael Cole & Debra gave a tease to the fans.A great video package was shown for The Buried Alive Match.Michael Cole was at the graveside area & he had to mention the tombstone weighed 3,000 pounds.The New Age Outlaws Road Dogg Jesse James & BA Billy Gunn Def The Acolytes Faarooq & Bradshaw by disqualificationhalf a starKen Shamrock & The Big Boss Man interfered causing the disqualification. Triple H came down to make save he got The Outlaws out of there. Then The Acolytes started fighting Shamrock & The Boss Man. Undertaker's music hit Undertaker spoke over The System he said tonight will be the final chapter he said he claimed Austin's soul this past Monday Night tonight he will claim his very existence since Monday you've grown weaker while my Ministry grows stronger. Heat goes off the air then we get to The Pay Per View which this is from The VHS version cause it has exclusive footage where they're putting together the graveside area & The Rock was at Planet Hollywood. Where he was really putting himself over.The opening was very good Freddie Blassie did a wonderful job with the voice over.Mark Henry & D'Lo Brown with Jacqueline & Terri Runnels Def The Godfather & Val Venis with The H  o's.The Godfather gave The H  o's to Val for the night he said he's got The Yule Log if they got the fireplace.They showed what Mankind did to The Rock from earlier.They show The Rock with The McMahon's backstageThe Headbangers Mosh & Thrasher Def Golga & Kurrgan with Silva & Luna *how all this came about was that The ICP turned on The Oddities & they cut off Luna's haira poor match but it involved The Oddities so that says it allbackstage Patterson & Brisco offered to go after Mankind McMahon said he will talk to him by himself.Steve Blackman Def Owen Hart by countout **an ok match  it would've been a halfway decent had it had a winner.In the back Vince was looking for Mankind he saw a sign on the door of The Boiler Room that said Mankind's Office. Mankind said come on in Dad.The BroodGangrelEdge & ChristianDefThe JOB SquadAl Snow 2 Cold Scorpio& Bob Holly **another ok matchStriptease MatchGoldust Def Jeff Jarrett with Debra by disqualification * & 3 quarters of a starThe King ask Michael Cole if he had ever seen a Woman strip you know 1 you didn't have to inflate. At 1st Jeff Jarrett won  but then WWF Commissioner Shawn Michaels reversed the decision he made Debra strip Shawn was yelling "I LOVE MY JOB!" The Blue Blazer & Jeff Jarrett stopped it from continuing to some pretty loud boos.WWF Tag Team ChampionshipThe New Age Outlaws Road Dogg Jesse James & BA Billy Gunn Def Ken Shamrock & The Big Boss Man with Shawn Michaels** & quarter of a star D Generation X was banned from ringside a half way decent matchA really good video package was shown on how The Rock became The WWF ChampionIn the back Vince tells The Rock let's just play along with MankindWWF ChampionshipMankind Def Champion The Rock with Vince & Shane McMahon ***Vince announced that The Rock didn't tap or say I quit so the title stayed with The Rockthis match had decent storytelling you know cause when Foley went at it in the ring he fought pretty liberally but McMahon told The Referee to disqualify Mankind if he breaks anymore rules. So when he went for what looked like a low blow on The Rock Vince told The Referee to disqualify Mankind so Mankind gave a piledriver to The Referee then he beat up a Time Keeper it really told that Mankind wanted to win the title so he could finally say he has been a World Champion the fans really wanted to see Mankind win the title but he was crushed he went after Vince & put The Mandible Claw on McMahon. It took the efforts of Shane McMahon, Pat Patterson, Gerald Brisco, Ken Shamrock & The Big Boss Man to put Mankind out. Mankind got 1 more shot on the very infamous January 4th 1999 episode of RAW which I am going to cover in my Good Wrestling TV reviews.A great video package for The Stone Cold vs The Undertaker Buried Alive MatchBURIED ALIVE MATCHStone Cold Steve Austin Def The Undertaker with Paul Bearer **** per Austin's win he qualified for The Royal Rumble. This was good brawl interference by Kane didn't hurt Austin brought a Back Hoe into the arena I couldn't help but chuckle. Call me crazy I gave it 4 stars it was a lot of fun.What do you know an In Your House I think is solid for once the title match was good. Buried Alive was what it was expected to be. A Tag title match that was halfway decent. The undercard is ok like Owen Hart vs Steve Blackman, Jarrett & Goldust, The Brood & JOB Squad. The only bad matches were D'Lo Brown & Mark Henry vs The Godfather & Val Venis & The Headbangers vs The Oddities. I recommend it if you see The VHS at a Pawn Shop for like $5 or a bootleg seller has it don't pass it up next we enter an even bigger year for The WWF 1999 & will start off with of course The Royal Rumble.
summary: WWF Rock Bottom In Your House 8/10

reviewText: I liked it from the very start from Val Venis and the Godfather facing off against D'lo Brown and Mark Henry all the way to the Buried Alive Match featuring the "Texas Rattlesnake" Stone Cold Steve Austin facing off against the "Phenom" The Undertaker and I liked it when Undertaker's brother Kane came and he cost Undertaker the match which lead to Kane tombstoning the Undertaker and Austin came and he buried Undertaker alive. It was the bomb and at the end the referee which was Earl Hebner congratulated Austin for his match and they both drank beer. Thank you very much, yours truly, Zaida M Quijano and P.S., I never seen this one before.
